{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778978967859,"sessionID":"ses_1cc98b089ffeqDgg64MacYW8kG","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"webfetch","callID":"call_mICCRPlKWXy9jSYNGSGK07v4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"url":"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/agricultural-and-biological-sciences/mesosalpinx","format":"markdown","timeout":60},"output":"  Mesosalpinx - an overview | ScienceDirect Topics                  [Skip to Main content](#main_content \"Skip to Main content\")\n\n[![Elsevier logo](https://sdfestaticassets-us-east-1.sciencedirectassets.com/shared-assets/24/images/elsevier-non-solus-new-grey.svg)ScienceDirect](/)\n\n-   [Journals & Books](/browse/journals-and-books)\n\n-   Help\n    \n-   [Search](/search)\n    \n\n[My account](/user/login?targetURL=%2Ftopics%2Fagricultural-and-biological-sciences%2Fmesosalpinx&from=globalheader)\n\n[Sign in](/user/institution/login?targetURL=%2Ftopics%2Fagricultural-and-biological-sciences%2Fmesosalpinx)\n\n# Mesosalpinx\n\nIn subject area: [Agricultural and Biological Sciences](/topics/agricultural-and-biological-sciences)\n\n## Also in subject areas:\n\n-   [Medicine and Dentistry](/topics/medicine-and-dentistry/mesosalpinx)\n-   [Veterinary Science and Veterinary Medicine](/topics/veterinary-science-and-veterinary-medicine/mesosalpinx)\n\nAbout this page\n\nSet alert[Discover more topics](/topics)\n\n1.  ## On this page\n    \n\n## On this page\n\n-   [Chapters and Articles](#chapters-articles)\n-   [Related Terms](#related-terms)\n-   [Recommended Publications](#recommended-publications)\n\n## On this page\n\n-   [Chapters and Articles](#chapters-articles)\n-   [Related Terms](#related-terms)\n-   [Recommended Publications](#recommended-publications)\n\n## Chapters and Articles\n\nYou might find these chapters and articles relevant to this topic.\n\nChapter\n\n## [Female Reproduction](/science/article/pii/B978012801238364401X)\n\n[2018, Encyclopedia of Reproduction (Second Edition)](/referencework/9780128151457)Wipawee Winuthayanon, Shuai Li\n\n### Mesosalpinx\n\nSerous layer of the Fallopian tube, also known as mesosalpinx (Fig. 2A), is the outer tissue layer that wraps around the Fallopian tube and is part of the peritoneal cavity lining. Mesosalpinx is composed of epithelial cells of mesothelium and a mesh of serous membrane lining (interstitial connective tissue). The mesothelium is the outermost boundary of the serous layer and is directly exposed to the pelvic cavity. Underneath the mesothelium is the serous membrane, surrounding the muscle layer. Blood vessels, nervous system, and lymphatic system are located within the serous membrane (Pauerstein and Eddy, 1979).\n\nThe vascular system of the Fallopian tube is supplied by the uterine and ovarian arteries. The capillaries innervate into the muscle and mucosal layers (Fig. 2A). This vascular system not only is critical for circulation but also is crucial for embryo development (Garcia-Pascual et al., 1996). Blood flow in the Fallopian tube is responsible for the generation and maintenance of the tubal fluid, which nourishes and protects gametes and embryos against external stress.\n\nThe nervous innervation of the Fallopian tube depends on the segment and the type of sensory nervous system. For example, the sympathetic nervous system from the celiac plexus innervates the infundibulum and the ampullary portion adjacent to the infundibulum, whereas the ampullary portion adjacent to the isthmic region and the isthmus receive sympathetic nervous supply from the inferior mesenteric plexus. For the parasympathetic nervous system, similar areas of the infundibulum and the ampulla are innervated by ovarian plexus, and similar areas of the isthmus and part of the ampulla are innervated by pelvic plexus of the pelvic nerve. Innervation of the nervous system runs parallel with the vascular system.\n\nThe lymphatic system of the Fallopian tube is supplied by the ovarian and uterine lymphatic systems, which originate from the iliac and lateral aortic nodes. Lymphatic system runs into the serous and mucosal layer enabling the lymphocyte to infiltrate and protect the Fallopian tube from pathogen infection. In the Fallopian tube, the lymphatic system acts as a drainage to reabsorb tubal fluid. The major immune cells found in the Fallopian tubes are the T cells. B cells are rare in this tissue (Otsuki et al., 1989).\n\nShow more\n\n[View chapter](/science/article/pii/B978012801238364401X)[Explore book](/referencework/9780128151457)\n\n[Read full chapter](/science/article/pii/B978012801238364401X)\n\nURL: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B978012801238364401X\n\nReference work[\n\n![Encyclopedia of Reproduction (Second Edition)](https://ars.els-cdn.com/content/image/3-s2.0-C20151067187-cov200h.gif)\n\n2018, Encyclopedia of Reproduction (Second Edition)\n\n](/referencework/9780128151457)Wipawee Winuthayanon, Shuai Li\n\nChapter\n\n## [Oviduct/Uterine Tube Obstruction](/science/article/pii/B9780323910156000650)\n\n[2022, Comparative Veterinary Anatomy](/book/9780323910156)Candace Lyman, Patricia Sertich\n\n### Mesosalpinx and associated structures\n\nThe connective tissue directly surrounding and supporting the uterine tube (Fig. 13.6-5) originates from the broad ligament and is termed the **mesosalpinx**. (Fig. 13.6-5). The mesosalpinx arises from the lateral surface of the **mesovarium**, which is the portion of the broad ligament that surrounds and supports the ovary. (The reader is referred to Case 13.3 for more information on the broad ligament.)\n\n### Hydrosalpinx and Salpingitis: Mares Are Not Elegant Cows\n\nContrary to the mare, salpingitis and subsequent hydrosalpinx has historically been a cause of infertility in bovids. Both were thought to occur, in part, due to the previous practice of manual enucleation of the CL per rectum. Hemorrhage descending from the ovary would result in hematoma formation in the ovarian bursa, fibrous adhesion formation, and oviductal occlusion. With the development of injectable PG, manual enucleation of the CL is no longer recommended. An additional precursor to salpingitis can be inflammation or pathological fluid within the uterus of the bovid; these are more likely to result in uterine tubal pathology since no uterine tubal papillae exist to prevent reflux; rather, the tip of the uterine horn simply attenuates to form a uterine tube—i.e., oviduct. Not surprisingly, large animal clinicians may be tempted to erroneously extrapolate information from one species to the other in cases of infertility in the mare.\n\nWith rare exceptions, salpingitis and hydrosalpinx have not been associated with infertility in the mare. Perhaps this is due to the dorsal position of the uterine tubes at the tips of the uterine horns and the prominent musculature of the uterine tubal papillae, as both characteristics could potentially be adept in preventing uterine tubal reflux. While studies have shown contradicting evidence, it appears that histopathological evidence of salpingitis is more common than previously believed—in many of these studies, uterine tubal inflammation was classified as “slight” and limited to lymphocytes. So, while inflammation may have been identified more frequently than originally expected based on clinical impression, unlike cattle, these findings may not have a significant effect on fertility. Rarely, hydrosalpinx has been diagnosed in mares related to ascending infection or traumatic injury. Congenital segmental aplasia is also a viable explanation, but with a limited frequency, of hydrosalpinx in the mare.\n\nShow more\n\n[View chapter](/science/article/pii/B9780323910156000650)[Explore book](/book/9780323910156)\n\n[Read full chapter](/science/article/pii/B9780323910156000650)\n\nURL: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9780323910156000650\n\nBook[\n\n![Comparative Veterinary Anatomy](https://ars.els-cdn.com/content/image/3-s2.0-C20160010033-cov200h.gif)\n\n2022, Comparative Veterinary Anatomy\n\n](/book/9780323910156)Candace Lyman, Patricia Sertich\n\nChapter\n\n## [Female Reproduction](/science/article/pii/B978012801238364401X)\n\n[2018, Encyclopedia of Reproduction (Second Edition)](/referencework/9780128151457)Wipawee Winuthayanon, Shuai Li\n\n### Cell Biology and Physiology of the Fallopian Tube\n\n#### Mesosalpinx\n\nSerous layer of the Fallopian tube, also known as mesosalpinx (Fig. 2A), is the outer tissue layer that wraps around the Fallopian tube and is part of the peritoneal cavity lining. Mesosalpinx is composed of epithelial cells of mesothelium and a mesh of serous membrane lining (interstitial connective tissue). The mesothelium is the outermost boundary of the serous layer and is directly exposed to the pelvic cavity. Underneath the mesothelium is the serous membrane, surrounding the muscle layer. Blood vessels, nervous system, and lymphatic system are located within the serous membrane (Pauerstein and Eddy, 1979).\n\nThe vascular system of the Fallopian tube is supplied by the uterine and ovarian arteries. The capillaries innervate into the muscle and mucosal layers (Fig. 2A). This vascular system not only is critical for circulation but also is crucial for embryo development (Garcia-Pascual et al., 1996). Blood flow in the Fallopian tube is responsible for the generation and maintenance of the tubal fluid, which nourishes and protects gametes and embryos against external stress.\n\nThe nervous innervation of the Fallopian tube depends on the segment and the type of sensory nervous system. For example, the sympathetic nervous system from the celiac plexus innervates the infundibulum and the ampullary portion adjacent to the infundibulum, whereas the ampullary portion adjacent to the isthmic region and the isthmus receive sympathetic nervous supply from the inferior mesenteric plexus. For the parasympathetic nervous system, similar areas of the infundibulum and the ampulla are innervated by ovarian plexus, and similar areas of the isthmus and part of the ampulla are innervated by pelvic plexus of the pelvic nerve. Innervation of the nervous system runs parallel with the vascular system.\n\nThe lymphatic system of the Fallopian tube is supplied by the ovarian and uterine lymphatic systems, which originate from the iliac and lateral aortic nodes. Lymphatic system runs into the serous and mucosal layer enabling the lymphocyte to infiltrate and protect the Fallopian tube from pathogen infection. In the Fallopian tube, the lymphatic system acts as a drainage to reabsorb tubal fluid. The major immune cells found in the Fallopian tubes are the T cells. B cells are rare in this tissue (Otsuki et al., 1989).\n\n#### Myosalpinx\n\nMyosalpinx is the tubal muscle of the Fallopian tube, which consists of an outer longitudinal muscle layer and an inner circular muscle layer. These two muscle layers control the Fallopian tubal contraction responsible for various reproductive functions. First, the contraction retains the unfertilized oocyte in the ampullary region of the Fallopian tube. This is achieved through contraction of the muscle in the ampullary–isthmic junction. Ampullary–isthmic contraction also prevents polyspermy by restricting the rate of the sperm entering the ampulla (Ezzati et al., 2014). Both the ampullary–isthmic junction and uterotubal junction are pivotal for the timing of embryo implantation in the uterus. It takes the oocyte approximately 8 h to reach the ampullary–isthmic junction; then, after fertilization, the zygote is retained in the isthmus for approximately 72 h (Croxatto et al., 1978; Lyons et al., 2006). However, the time an embryo spends in the Fallopian tube is species-specific (Croxatto, 2002). Overaccelerated embryo transport results in premature arrival of the embryo to the uterus, in which the uterine environment is not conducive for embryo implantation (Adams, 1979).\n\nUnlike intestinal smooth muscle, muscle contraction of the Fallopian tube not only is controlled by adrenergic neurons but also is regulated by P4 and prostaglandins (Wanggren et al., 2008). Progesterone and prostaglandin receptors have been recently identified on the telocyte, a newly discovered cell type in human Fallopian tubes (Cretoiu and Cretoiu, 2016). Telocytes are interstitial cajal-like cells with long cytoplasmic processes (Cretoiu et al., 2009) that reside in the interstitial connective tissue layer of the Fallopian tube. The function of telocytes is not yet fully understood. However, evidence indicates that a reduction in telocytes results in defective peristaltic movement of the Fallopian tube (Roatesi et al., 2015).\n\n#### Endosalpinx\n\nEndosalpinx is the inner mucosal layer of the Fallopian tube responsible for transporting gametes and embryos and tubal fluid secretions. The endosalpinx is composed of epithelial cells and the lamina propria mucosa; the latter is a network of connective tissue with a mixed cell population. The epithelial tissue on the inner surface of the Fallopian tube is made up of two main cell types: ciliated epithelial cells and nonciliated secretory epithelial cells (Fig. 2B and C). Beneath the lining of epithelium is the lamina propria, which consists of fibroblast, immune, and progenitor cells. Mucosal layer forms dense internal folds, increasing the surface area of epithelial cell lining to achieve high fluid secretory rate (Fig. 2A).\n\nMulticiliated epithelial cells in the Fallopian tube are featured with a classical 9 + 2 microtubule structure (axoneme) to create a beating movement (Lodish et al., 2000). The movement of axoneme requires adenosine triphosphate (ATP) as the energy source. Elevated E2 concentration stimulates ATP production at the apical surface of the epithelial cells and results in an increase in ciliary beat frequency. In rabbits, the absence of calcium results in nonbeating cilium. This suggests the mechanism involves a calcium-dependent ciliary regulation (Verdugo, 1980), potentially through a voltage-gated calcium channel (Doerner et al., 2015). Adrenomedullin-induced activation of calcitonin-gene-related peptide receptor is also involved in ciliary beating (Liao et al., 2013; Liao et al., 2011). In this adrenomedullin-related mechanism, E2 stimulates the secretory epithelia to produce cyclic adenosine monophosphate, which subsequently promotes adrenomedullin activation in ciliated cells.\n\nNongenomic membrane-bound progesterone receptors (mPGRs) have been observed on the apical surface of epithelial cells in the Fallopian tube. mPGRs facilitate rapid cellular signaling pathways activated by P4 and regulate ciliary beat frequency. Therefore, an alteration of these pathways could cause defective ciliary function and lead to embryo transport defects.\n\nCiliary beat activity of the epithelial cells results in oocyte pickup, embryo transport, and tubal fluid flow. Tubal fluid flow acts as a carrier, allowing embryo transport from the Fallopian tube to the uterus. Simultaneously, the fluid flow removes cell debris within the lumen (Miki and Clapham, 2013). The direction of the fluid flow is usually from the ovary toward the uterus in mammals. However, tubal flow in pigs progresses toward the ovary, which suggests that fluid flow orientation varies between species (Gaddum-Rosse and Blandau, 1976).\n\nApproximately, 60% of epithelial cell lining is nonciliated epithelial (secretory) cells. The percentage differs between tube regions (Pedrero-Badillo et al., 2013). These secretory epithelial cells are morphologically distinct from ciliated epithelia. Not only the nonciliated epithelial cells lack cilia at the apical membrane, but also the cell bodies show apical protrusion into the lumen, also known as intercalary cells or peg cells (Fig. 2B and C). The cytosol of secretory cells contains an extensive Golgi network and apical granules. Secretory cells mainly secrete growth factors, nutrients, antimicrobial agents, and anticellular stress agents into the tubal fluid. Some of the secretory factors are enzymatically active including proteases and peptidases, which could potentially harm the embryos. Recent findings demonstrate that E2 can have a protective effect on the embryo by reducing protease production within the mouse oviduct (Winuthayanon et al., 2015).\n\nThe lamina propria mucosa consists of connective tissue, secretory cells, microcapillary vessels, and a population of leucine-rich repeat-containing G-protein-coupled receptor 5 (LGR5)-positive progenitor cells. Lamina propria provides structural and nutritional support for the endosalpinx, while Lgr5-positive progenitor cells allow for tubal epithelial cell regeneration (Ng et al., 2014; Snegovskikh et al., 2014).\n\nShow more\n\n[View chapter](/science/article/pii/B978012801238364401X)[Explore book](/referencework/9780128151457)\n\n[Read full chapter](/science/article/pii/B978012801238364401X)\n\nURL: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B978012801238364401X\n\nReference work[\n\n![Encyclopedia of Reproduction (Second Edition)](https://ars.els-cdn.com/content/image/3-s2.0-C20151067187-cov200h.gif)\n\n2018, Encyclopedia of Reproduction (Second Edition)\n\n](/referencework/9780128151457)Wipawee Winuthayanon, Shuai Li\n\nChapter\n\n## [Female Reproductive System and Mammae](/science/article/pii/B9780323357753000187)\n\n[2017, Pathologic Basis of Veterinary Disease (Sixth Edition)](/book/9780323357753)Robert A. Foster\n\n### Hydrosalpinx.\n\nHydrosalpinx is a dilated and fluid-filled uterine tube. Obstruction of the uterine tube prevents normal fluid from exiting to the uterus. Obstruction results from previous salpingitis and scaring, from trauma in cattle after aggressive rectal palpation or manual expression of a corpus luteum, ovarian hematoma, or from cystic dilation of duct remnants of embryonic tissues or segmental aplasia. Macroscopically, there is dilation of the uterine tube with clear fluid so that it becomes thin-walled, tortuous, and appears to be longer than normal.\n\nLesions commonly encountered in dogs and cats are duct remnants in the mesosalpinx, more often of mesonephric duct (simple tubular structures lined by low columnar to cuboidal cells) than of paramesonephric duct (lined by a folded mucosa similar to the uterine tube mucosa) origin. Mesonephric and paramesonephric duct remnants are described in the discussion on periovarian cysts in the section on the Ovary.\n\nShow more\n\n[View chapter](/science/article/pii/B9780323357753000187)[Explore book](/book/9780323357753)\n\n[Read full chapter](/science/article/pii/B9780323357753000187)\n\nURL: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9780323357753000187\n\nBook[\n\n![Pathologic Basis of Veterinary Disease (Sixth Edition)](https://ars.els-cdn.com/content/image/3-s2.0-C20130155523-cov200h.gif)\n\n2017, Pathologic Basis of Veterinary Disease (Sixth Edition)\n\n](/book/9780323357753)Robert A. Foster\n\nChapter\n\n## [Clinical Reproductive Anatomy and Physiology of the Mare](/science/article/pii/B9780721693231500106)\n\n[2007, Current Therapy in Large Animal Theriogenology (Second Edition)](/book/9780721693231)TIMOTHY J. EVANS, ... VENKATASESHU K. GANJAM\n\n### Internal structure and function.\n\nThere is a divergence in the internal structure of the portions of the oviduct and this structural alteration suggests that the primary functions of the uterine tube vary from the ovarian to the uterine extremities. The muscular layer (myosalpinx or tunica muscularis) consists primarily of an inner layer of circularly arranged muscle fibers covered by an outer layer of longitudinally oriented fibers. These longitudinally arranged fibers are continuous with the smooth muscle present in the mesosalpinx. There are very few muscle fibers in the fimbriae, and the tunica muscularis of the ampulla is thin. The muscular layer of the isthmus, however, is very well developed. A sphincter of circular smooth muscle is formed at the uterotubal junction.1,4\n\nThe mucosa of the infundibulum is highly folded longitudinally and covered by columnar epithelium, which is frequently ciliated. Changes in the estrous cycle are reflected by alterations in ciliogenesis and ciliary action. The mucosa of the ampulla is extremely plicated with primary, secondary, and even tertiary folds. This complexity of folding is more obvious in the mare than in ruminants, but the mucosa of the isthmus has much less folding than that of ampulla.1,4,7\n\nThe oocyte with its cumulus of granulosa cells is swept into the infundibulum by cilia. Very little, if any, follicular fluid enters the uterine tube following ovulation. The proximal portions of the oviducts provide a conduit for transport of the oocyte to the site of fertilization at the junction of the ampulla and the isthmus. The uterotubal junction allows spermatozoa to enter the isthmus following breeding, yet there is no reflux of uterine contaminants into the oviduct. The isthmus provides sites for capacitation and storage of spermatozoa while they await an oocyte to fertilize. The nonciliated epithelium of the uterine tube is predominantly secretory in nature and produces proteins and glycosaminoglycans. These secretory products may play a role in mediating capacitation of spermatozoa, fertilization of the ovum, and early embryonic cleavage. Preovulatory follicular fluid has a role in regulating oviductal protein production in vitro and in vivo (uterine tube ipsilateral to ovulation).4 The mare is unique among domestic mammals in that only fertilized oocytes (developing embryos) enter the uterus approximately 6 days following ovulation. Unfertilized ova are retained in the middle third of the uterine tube for several estrous cycles among collagenous material that may contain cells similar to fibroblasts. Some have suggested this selective transport of fertilized oocytes is the initial step in “maternal recognition of pregnancy” in the mare.1,4,5\n\nShow more\n\n[View chapter](/science/article/pii/B9780721693231500106)[Explore book](/book/9780721693231)\n\n[Read full chapter](/science/article/pii/B9780721693231500106)\n\nURL: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9780721693231500106\n\nBook[\n\n![Current Therapy in Large Animal Theriogenology (Second Edition)](https://ars.els-cdn.com/content/image/3-s2.0-B9780721693231X50016-cov200h.gif)\n\n2007, Current Therapy in Large Animal Theriogenology (Second Edition)\n\n](/book/9780721693231)TIMOTHY J. EVANS, ... VENKATASESHU K. GANJAM\n\nChapter\n\n## [African Hedgehogs](/science/article/pii/B9781416066217000300)\n\n[2012, Ferrets, Rabbits, and Rodents (Third Edition)](/book/9781416066217)Evelyn Ivey DVM, Diplomate ABVP (Avian), James W. Carpenter MS, DVM, Diplomate ACZM\n\n### Reproductive\n\nAn unrolled hedgehog’s gender is easily determined; the male has a conspicuous prepuce that opens on the midabdomen, whereas the female’s urogenital opening is a few millimeters cranial to the anus. The penis has a prominent glans that protrudes laterally into horn-like structures.4 There is no scrotal sac; the testes are located in a para-anal recess,4 are surrounded by fat, and can be palpated in reproductively active males. Male accessory glands include paired prostate glands, seminal vesicles, bulbourethral glands, and Cowper’s-like glands.58 The uterus is bicornate with no uterine body but rather a continuous lumen over the cervix. There is a single cervix and a long vagina that is always patent. A fan-shaped gland, homologous to the Cowper’s-like gland of the male, lies on each side of the vagina. The urethral opening is located in the distal vagina, several millimeters from the vulva. The mesosalpinx and ovarian bursa are fat-laden, and the fallopian tubes are relatively short and emerge from the side of each uterine horn.4 Females have three pairs of mammary glands.45\n\nAfrican hedgehogs are polyestrous and breed throughout the year in captivity. The estrus cycle for *A. albiventris* empirically seems to be similar to that of other hedgehog species, for which the estrus cycle has been reported to be 3 to 17 days of estrus followed by 1 to 5 days of diestrus.58 There is some indirect evidence to suggest that ovulation is induced.4,58 Sterile matings with pseudopregnancy may occur. Although the gestation period is 34 to 37 days, it is possible that delayed implantation may occur and extend the apparent gestation period to 40 days.58 Hedgehogs are born hairless, with closed eyes and ears. At birth, the spines are buried within a layer of skin; within the first few hours, the spines are exposed by an inflating and subsequent deflating of the skin with fluid and removal of the covering by the mother. These first spines are white, but they are replaced by darker spines over the first 3 days of life. Colostral transfer is believed to occur early in lactation.\n\nShow more\n\n[View chapter](/science/article/pii/B9781416066217000300)[Explore book](/book/9781416066217)\n\n[Read full chapter](/science/article/pii/B9781416066217000300)\n\nURL: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9781416066217000300\n\nBook[\n\n![Ferrets, Rabbits, and Rodents (Third Edition)](https://ars.els-cdn.com/content/image/3-s2.0-C20090602828-cov200h.gif)\n\n2012, Ferrets, Rabbits, and Rodents (Third Edition)\n\n](/book/9781416066217)Evelyn Ivey DVM, Diplomate ABVP (Avian), James W. Carpenter MS, DVM, Diplomate ACZM\n\nChapter\n\n## [The Cat](/science/article/pii/B9780124104600000073)\n\n[2019, The Dissection of Vertebrates (Third Edition)](/book/9780124104600)Gerardo De Iuliis PhD, Dino Pulerà MScBMC, CMI\n\n### Key Terms: Female Reproductive System\n\n**anal glands**\n\n**body** of the **uterus**\n\n**broad ligament**\n\n**cervix** of the **uterus**\n\n**clitoris**\n\n**fimbriae**\n\n**infundibulum**\n\n**mammary glands**\n\n**mesometrium**\n\n**mesosalpinx**\n\n**mesovarium**\n\n**ostium tubae**\n\n**ovarian ligament**\n\n**ovary**\n\n**round ligament**\n\n**suspensory ovarian ligament**\n\n**urethral orifice**\n\n**urogenital aperture** (vulva)\n\n**urogenital sinus** (vaginal vestibule, urogenital canal)\n\n**uterine horn**\n\n**uterine tube** (fallopian tube)\n\n**vagina**\n\nShow more\n\n[View chapter](/science/article/pii/B9780124104600000073)[Explore book](/book/9780124104600)\n\n[Read full chapter](/science/article/pii/B9780124104600000073)\n\nURL: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9780124104600000073\n\nBook[\n\n![The Dissection of Vertebrates (Third Edition)](https://ars.els-cdn.com/content/image/3-s2.0-C20110087203-cov200h.gif)\n\n2019, The Dissection of Vertebrates (Third Edition)\n\n](/book/9780124104600)Gerardo De Iuliis PhD, Dino Pulerà MScBMC, CMI\n\nChapter\n\n## [Old and New World Camelids](/science/article/pii/B9780702072338000379)\n\n[2019, Veterinary Reproduction and Obstetrics (Tenth Edition)](/book/9780702072338)Gayle D. Hallowell\n\n### South American Camelidae\n\nThere are four species of New World camelids: *Lama glama* (llama), *Lama pacos* (alpaca), *Lama guanacoe* (guanaco), and *Vicugna vicugna* (Vicuna). They originated in North America and have the greatest numbers in South America but are now reared worldwide as companion animals and for high quality fibre production. Outside of South America, they are reared much less for their meat. Adult llamas weigh 130 to 160 kg and can reach 1.9 m in height. Alpacas weigh between 40 and 65 kg and stand up to 1.5 m in height. There are two phenotypes of alpaca – Huacaya (Fig. 37.1) and Suri; they are different in appearance and the latter is less well adapted at very high altitudes (> 4200m; Fernandez-Saga 1975). The Huacaya alpacas have a shorter, denser coat and shorter nose than the Suri. Guanaco and llamas are a similar weight and size. Vicunas are the smallest of the four species; they weigh between 30 and 50 kg and stand a maximum of 1.3 m in height. They are primarily found in Peru and are a protected species. Normally, a healthy female can produce a cria every year, with 20 crias produced in her lifetime. All four species can interbreed and produce fertile hybrids. Hybridisation between a male Arabian camel and a female guanaco has also been achieved (Skidmore et al. 2001). There are still many unknowns regarding camelid reproduction compared with other species, but this chapter will aim to present current understanding, which will primarily be based on what is known in llamas, alpacas, and then camels.\n\n#### Normal Reproductive Anatomy\n\n##### Female\n\nThe ovaries of the llama and alpaca are ellipsoid to globular. Their size is dependent on the structures on the ovary being approximately 1 to 2 cm in diameter. In adults, multiple follicles of 2 to 5 mm are found on the ovarian surface (Fowler et al. 1998). These can be identified using transrectal ultrasound up to 3 mm in diameter; larger follicles and corpora lutea can be palpated *per rectum.* They have long, tortuous, firm uterine tubes (1–2 cm), which lie within the mesosalpinx. The uterus is bicornuate, which resembles a letter ‘Y’. The body is short (3–6 cm) and horns are long (20–25 cm), with the left horn being slightly larger than the right, even in the nulliparous female. The nongravid uterus lies within the pelvic inlet. The uterus and cervix appear heterogenous during follicular dominance, whereas cervical folds become prominent and increase in echogenicity during the luteal phase. The uterine horns become straighter and have increased tone with increased oestrogen concentrations, whereas they are curled with minimal tone with increased progesterone concentrations. The cervix is 2 to 5 cm long and 2 to 4 cm in diameter, with two to three spiral-shaped cervical rings. The vagina is 10 to 15 cm long in the alpaca and 15 to 25 cm in the llama with a diameter of 2 to 5 cm. The vulva is small and does not change in appearance with changes in hormones or pregnancy.\n\n##### Male\n\nThe scrotum is nonpendulous and is situated high in the perineal region and level with the ischial arch. The testes are relatively small compared with ruminants of comparable body size, and the epididymis lies on the dorsal border of the testis with the head situated at the cranial pole. The testes develop slowly. They are present in the scrotum at birth but are hard to palpate; at 6 months, they are small and soft, but by 12 months, they can be easily palpated and the testis and epididymis easily differentiated. It is at around 12 months of age that future herd sires can be selected based on testis size and other physical characteristics. The prepuce, which is flattened and triangular in shape, lies in the perineal region. The glans penis and prepuce are attached until the male reaches 2 to 3 years of age, such that the penis cannot be exteriorised in young males. When animals are not sexually aroused, the preputial orifice faces caudally. When sexually aroused, the developed preputial musculature allows for redirection of the orifice cranially. The fibroelastic penis is 35 to 45 cm in length and is retracted by the presence of a prescrotal sigmoid flexure. The glans penis is 10 to 12 cm in length, and the distal tip consists of a cartilaginous process. The urethral orifice is at the base of the cartilaginous process and not at the tip (Tibary & Vaughan 2006). The curved nature of the cartilaginous process enables penetration of the cervix through rotational and thrusting movements, allowing uterine deposition of semen. A dorsal urethral diverticulum prevents insertion of a catheter along the urethra into the bladder. Camelids have no seminal vesicles but have well developed bulbourethral glands and ampullae of the vas deferens.\n\n#### Safe Restraint for Reproductive Examination\n\nThe majority of llamas and alpacas are relatively easy to handle. In many animals a calm, quiet approach will allow it to be done without sedation. Halters, a stable area, a wall to prevent the animal moving away from the examiner and specific crushes, if available, can allow a reproductive examination to be performed safely and effectively. A small number of animals, usually males, may require sedation using opioids or alpha-2 agonists combined with opioids. Usually, adverse responses to handling include spitting, kicking, and biting.\n\n#### Puberty, Sexual Maturity, and the Breeding Season\n\nThe precise onset of puberty in llamas and alpacas is unknown, but nutritional status and environmental conditions are thought to play a key role. Increases in ovarian hormone production have been recorded in well-developed llamas at 5 months, and ovarian activity detected in alpacas at 10 months. A relationship exists between successful mating and body weight with successful mating occurring in alpacas at 12 to 14 months at a body weight of 40 kg. It is recommended that llamas and alpacas are first mated at 2 years of age or at two-thirds of their final body weight to prevent stunting of the dam and dystocia.\n\nFirst production of spermatozoa in ejaculate has not been studied in this group, but puberty is thought to occur between 18 months and 2 years of age. Domesticated individuals are not used for breeding until 3 years of age (Bravo 2014).\n\nWhether these species as a group are seasonal breeders is controversial. It appears to be more closely related to environmental conditions or management strategies rather than seasons per se. In their harsh natural habitat, they are seasonal breeders, in that they display sexual activity and give birth in the warm, rainy season. However, when reared in milder climates, they mate and give birth all year round. Thus they are nonseasonal breeders but can become so if required by environmental and nutritional factors.\n\n#### Ovarian Activity, Mating, and Ovulation\n\nThese species are induced ovulators, requiring mating to trigger the LH surge required for ovulation. Thus they do not have regular oestrous cycles. Ovarian activity is thus described regarding the follicular and luteal phase. It is well documented, using a variety of modalities, that there are repeated follicular waves that regress without ovulation in the absence of mating. In a follicular wave, which comprises a very large number of individual follicles, often too numerous to count, some reach 4 to 5 mm in diameter, of which one becomes the dominant follicle; the others then undergo atresia and regress. The number of follicles is inversely proportional to the size of the dominant follicle (Vaughan 2002). Before the final regression of the dominant follicle, a new follicular wave develops, resulting in the presence of simultaneously regressing and growing follicles; this is known as ‘overlapping follicular waves’. These are reported to occur for about 30% of a female's lifespan. It is not possible to differentiate by transrectal palpation or ultrasonography between 5 and 6 mm follicles that are growing or regressing.\n\nThe follicular wave duration is variable within and between species of camelids, being 20 to 25 days in llamas and 12 to 22 days in alpacas (Aba 2014). In llamas, the follicular growth phase is approximately 9 days, the plateau phase is 8 days, and the regression phase 8 days. In alpacas, the plateau phase is between 2 and 8 days, and the regression phase is 3 to 8 days. The maximum preovulatory size occurs 6 to 8 days into the growth phase in llamas, with the maximum diameter of the dominant follicle being 12 mm in llamas and 8 to 12 mm in alpacas. Follicles develop equally between the two ovaries. Peak plasma oestradiol-17β concentrations correspond with the maximal preovulatory size and occur 12 and 8 days from the beginning of the growth phase in llamas and alpacas, respectively. With overlapping follicular waves, oestradiol-17β concentrations remain elevated, causing the long periods of receptivity to the male (> 3 weeks) with only short periods stages when the male is rejected. Without follicular waves, when a preovulatory follicle (> 7 mm) is present, females will be receptive for several days. Males are usually rejected when plasma oestrogen concentrations are low but can be accepted even if preovulatory follicles are absent. There is a lack of information on the mechanisms surrounding follicular growth, but it does appear to be associated with changes in FSH secretions as occurs in other species (see Chapter 1). Anovulatory follicles have been described in llamas and alpacas – they last longer and are larger. Cystic follicles are also identified as structures larger than 12 to 14 mm and persisting for 25 to 30 days. They occur more frequently in nonmated animals, and some individuals appear to be more prone. It is debatable whether cystic and haemorrhagic follicles are one and the same; they do not secrete oestrogen and do not usually affect ovarian dynamics.\n\nThe males pursue females when they are in oestrus. The flehmen response is exhibited when the male sniffs the perineum, urine, or faeces of females; this is followed by the male lifting his head and opening his mouth, sometimes shaking the head rapidly. They do not curl the upper lip as in other species. Some females ‘cush’, that is, assume sternal recumbency when approached by a male, whereas others do not ‘cush’ until the male mounts and places pressure over their hindlimbs. Other receptive females often sit close to mating pairs. During mating, the males vocalise (a guttural sound called ‘orgling’), dilate their nostrils, flag their tails, and demonstrate slight tremors of ears and nostrils with excitement. The females, in contrast, are very passive, although they may move from sternal to lateral recumbency. Mating usually lasts 20 to 30 minutes, and ejaculation occurs throughout this period (dribble ejaculation). Females who are not receptive will spit, kick, scream, and run away but will occasionally ‘cush’ and submit to mating. Continuous contact between males and females inhibits the male's desire to mate, despite the presence of other receptive females. However, when males are introduced, most females will be mated in the first week (Bravo 2014).\n\nOvulation of one follicle occurs when a neural signal triggered by mating involving both mounting and intromission stimulates the secretion of GnRH and then LH. Ovulation is not triggered simply by mounting (Fernandez-Saga et al. 1970). Multiple matings do not improve ovulation rates. There appears to be an ovulation-inducing factor (OIF) in the seminal fluid that has a GnRH-like activity stimulating LH release, with a systemic rather than local effect (Paolicchi et al. 1999, Adams et al. 2005, Ratto et al. 2010). Injections of hCG, GnRH, and LH can also induce ovulation (Fernandez-Saga et al. 1970). Increased oestradiol 17-β concentrations are seen on the day of mating and for up to 24 hours, and then fall 2 to 3 days later. Ovulation occurs 24 to 48 hours after mating. Ovulation failure has been reported after 10% to 30% of natural matings (Bravo 1994), multiple ovulations reported in approximately 10% of natural matings (Vaughan & Tibary 2006), and spontaneous ovulations have a prevalence of 3% to 10% (Bravo & Sumar 1989, Sumar 1996), the mechanism of which is unknown (England et al. 1969). The size of the dominant follicle (> 7 mm) determines whether ovulation occurs (Bravo et al. 1991). If there is no ovulation but luteinisation of usually regressing follicles occurs, the luteinised follicles last for 5 days, and then a new dominant follicle develops in a further 5 to 7 days (Bravo et al. 1991). If there is no ovulation and no formation of a luteinised follicle, the female will remain receptive to the male.\n\n#### Pregnancy Diagnosis\n\nThere are many important aspects of breeding management, but timely and accurate pregnancy diagnosis plays a fundamental role. Once a female has passed a breeding soundness examination, she should be teased until receptive to the male, when she can be bred. Females should be teased 7 to 12 days after mating. Those females that are not receptive at 14, 21, and 28 days should be examined using transrectal ultrasound. If the female is receptive to the male, then she should be mated again. If after three mating attempts the female is still receptive to the male, an infertility investigation should be performed. Pregnancy evaluation, using transrectal ultrasound, should be performed at 14, 25, and 35 days and between 45 and 60 days (Pearson et al. 2014a); further examinations should be performed beyond this date if the animal has a history of pregnancy loss. Blood progesterone concentrations greater than 1 ng/mL can be used for pregnancy diagnosis but do not provide information regarding twinning or subsequent early pregnancy failure loss; it is not as reliable as ultrasonography. Transrectal palpation in large llamas can readily be performed, but examination in smaller llamas and alpacas is dependent on the hand size of the examiner. Care is required as in the horse. However, transrectal ultrasonography can be performed without the need to insert a hand or arm into the rectum by using an adapted stiffened linear transducer with a moderate to high frequency (7.5–13 MHz), mounted on a thin piece of plastic pipe.\n\nPlasma oestrone sulphate has two peaks during pregnancy but is most useful to measure in the last trimester (last 90 days; Bravo et al. 1996a, Aba et al. 1998). Relaxin concentrations can also be used for pregnancy diagnosis if measured after 85 days; site of production is unknown (Bravo et al. 1996a). After 85 days the uterus has extended beyond the pelvic brim so that transabdominal ultrasonography is most useful at this stage for pregnancy diagnosis and assessment of fetal viability. A lower frequency (5 MHz) microconvex or convex transducer will be optimal at this stage.\n\n#### Pregnancy and Parturition\n\nThe pregnant animal does not need specific care, although it is advisable to keep males away from females in the last trimester, as placental oestrogen production can lead to inappropriate mating attempts, which can cause vaginal trauma and disruption of the cervical plug. Almost all successful pregnancies are carried in the left uterine horn. Maternal recognition of pregnancy is not fully understood, but what is known suggests it is complex and occurs over a short time period, making embryo loss likely in early pregnancy. The CL is necessary for the maintenance of pregnancy throughout gestation. Progesterone initially falls 2 weeks before parturition and plummets along with oestradiol-17β in the last 24 hours. Gestation length is traditionally reported as 335 to 360 days in llamas and alpacas but may be significantly more variable outside South America, ranging from 320 to 400 days. Factors likely to influence gestation length include breed, fetal gender, season of year, nutrition, and sire and dam effects; twinning is rare. The placenta is similar to the mare and sow (see Chapter 4) and is classified as being diffuse, epitheliochorial, and microcotyledonary (Aba 2014).\n\nParturition usually occurs in the early hours of the day (07:00–13:00), which compliments their natural habitat and behaviours, when ambient temperatures plummet in the evening and at night, and allows for predator avoidance. This is particularly important as the dam does not lick the neonate dry nor does she consume the placenta. There is often minimal to no warning of impending parturition. Relaxation of the sacrosciatic ligament begins 2 weeks before parturition, vulval oedema a few days before, and elongation of the vulva on the day of parturition. The udder develops in the 2 weeks before parturition, normally with mammary oedema extending to the xiphoid. Colostrum is produced from 4 to 6 days before parturition. Changes in electrolytes of mammary gland secretions are not a reliable indicator of impending parturition.\n\nParturition is usually swift. The first stage varies greatly in length from 3 to 48 hours and manifests as inappetence, restlessness, anxiety, increased frequency of urination and defecation, repeated standing and ‘cushing’ as well as separation from the herd. Second stage labour usually lasts less than 30 minutes but can be longer in primiparous females. Normally, the head, then one forelimb, and then the second are delivered. Most fetuses are expelled with the dam standing. Expulsion of the placenta usually occurs in less than 30 to 60 minutes but may take up to 4 hours. There is rarely rejection of young, even when the female has poor nutritional status and mild to moderate illness of the dam. Alpaca crias weigh 6 to 8 kg and llama crias 9 to 14 kg at birth. Birth weight increases with age of dam. Perinatal mortality is reported to be low (6%; Bravo 2009).\n\nFemales may be receptive to males 24 hours after birth but are not fertile, as uterine involution has not occurred, and ovulatory follicles have not had time to develop. It is thus recommended not to breed until 2 to 3 weeks after parturition (Bravo 1994). Fertility increases from 30% at Day 10 to 70% at Day 30 postpartum (Bravo 1995).\n\n#### Induction of Parturition\n\nInduction of parturition can be undertaken due to fetal distress or ill health of the dam but is not an appropriate management procedure (Rodriguez et al. 2014). Before induction of parturition is attempted, the presence of uterine torsion, which is a common finding, should be ruled out (Rodriguez et al. 2014). To minimise the risk of perinatal asphyxia syndrome, induction should only be undertaken if gestation is longer than 330 days, and colostrum is being produced. Induction can be achieved (see Chapter 6) using prostaglandin F2α (dinoprost tromethamine) or its analogue cloprostenol; the latter is preferred as the former has been associated with causing respiratory distress in the dam (Rodriguez et al. 2014). Oxytocin and dexamethasone should not be used because they are ineffective, and dexamethasone can result in fetal death *in utero* (Bravo et al. 1996b).\n\n#### Dystocia\n\nThis is relatively rare, with 2% to 5% of animals needing assistance. Dystocia should be suspected if first stage labour lasts more than 6 hours and with increasing levels of pain or discomfort, or if second stage labour does not progress normally. Any abnormal discharge from the vulva (haemorrhagic or purulent) requires further evaluation.\n\nThe most common maternal causes of dystocia are failure of cervical dilatation and uterine torsion, but uterine inertia and fetopelvic disproportion (small pelvis) have also been reported (Tibary et al. 2008). Hypocalcaemia can cause uterine inertia. Dystocia as a result of fetomaternal disproportion due to small dam size is avoidable if animals are not bred until they are 65% of adult body weight and height.\n\nDystocia of fetal origin is usually due to fetopelvic disproportion (large fetus) or abnormal fetal disposition (see Chapter 14). Older llamas and alpacas produce larger fetuses, perhaps making this more likely. Dystocia due to fetal developmental malformation is rare.\n\n##### Uterine Torsion\n\nThis is a common cause of colic and occurs at 8 to 10 months gestation and at parturition. Clinical signs are variable and include general depression, excessive vocalisation, mild to severe signs of colic (circling, kicking at the abdomen, lying in lateral recumbency), diarrhoea, and anorexia. It can be corrected by rolling, or surgically after an exploratory laparotomy.\n\n##### Failure of or Incomplete Cervical Dilatation\n\nThis has been linked to long-term progesterone therapy used to maintain pregnancy or abnormal fetal disposition during first stage labour. Topical PGE1 (misoprostol) applied to the cervix can be used to aid delivery of a dead fetus. However, surgical removal of the fetus via a Caesarean is recommended if the fetus is alive.\n\n##### Abnormal Presentation, Position, or Posture\n\n###### Head and Neck Deviations\n\nThese are the most common cause of dystocia in camelids. Due to the very long neck, correction can be challenging. Epidural anaesthesia facilitates correction, particularly if combined with the use of a soft rope positioned in the mouth and behind the ears. If correction proves impossible, a congenital abnormality such as ankylosis should be considered, and delivery should be performed via a Caesarean section. In llamas, it is possible to perform fetotomy by removing the head and neck if the fetus is dead (see Chapters 14 and 15) with the dam heavily sedated.\n\n###### Carpal Flexion\n\nThis is relatively easy to correct if the fetus is repulsed and the foot cupped and lifted over the pelvic brim.\n\n##### Management After Dystocia\n\nAfter dystocia, the dam is at increased risk of postpartum complications such as postpartum metabolic derangements, haemorrhage, severe metritis, peritonitis, and sepsis; these are more likely after removal of a dead fetus. Fluid therapy should be instituted in animals demonstrating signs of hypovolaemia or shock. Antimicrobial therapy may be required, ideally using an intravenous, bacteriocidal, and broad spectrum agent such as trimethoprim sulpha.\n\nThe neonate often requires resuscitation, with attention to the airway to ensure an unobstructed airway. Mouth-to-snout resuscitation may be undertaken, but occasionally endotracheal intubation may be required. There is evidence in other species that oxygen is not beneficial and may be harmful during resuscitation attempts. Cardiovascular compromise may require chest compressions and administration of cardiac drugs, particularly the use of intravenous epinephrine (adrenaline). Doxopram is contraindicated in dystocia cases; it is ineffective for secondary apnoea, and because it increases cerebral oxygen demand, it can further predispose to perinatal asphyxia syndrome.\n\n#### Disorders and Diseases of Pregnancy\n\n##### Abortion\n\nDetermining the cause of abortion can be challenging, and a specific diagnosis is only reached in 30% of cases. There are a variety of causes of abortion, and as in other species, they can be infectious and noninfectious. Of the infectious causes, bacterial infections are the most prevalent. *Leptospira spp, Chlamydophila spp, Campylobacter fetus,* and *Listeria monocytogenes* have all been identified in camelids, as has *E. coli, Streptococcus spp, Trueperella pyogenes,* and *Psuedomonas spp.* Viral infection can also play a role, the most important of which is bovine viral diarrhoea virus (BVDV); persistently infected animals can occur as in cattle. The methods of diagnosis are the same as in cattle (see Chapter 24). Other viruses linked to abortion include equine herpes virus, equine arteritis virus, and blue tongue virus. The most common protozoal cause of abortion in camelids is *Neospora caninum,* but *Toxoplasma gondii* is also a suspected cause (Pearson et al. 2014b).\n\n\n...24138 bytes truncated...\n\nThe tool call succeeded but the output was truncated. Full output saved to: /github/home/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_e3368d125001e2HaS0PDkBZOC7\nUse the Task tool to have explore agent process this file with Grep and Read (with offset/limit). Do NOT read the full file yourself - delegate to save context.","metadata":{"truncated":true,"outputPath":"/github/home/.local/share/opencode/tool-output/tool_e3368d125001e2HaS0PDkBZOC7"},"title":"https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/agricultural-and-biological-sciences/mesosalpinx (text/html; charset=utf-8)","time":{"start":1778978967255,"end":1778978967855}},"id":"prt_e3368ced3001LiGU4WDVAyPr6P","sessionID":"ses_1cc98b089ffeqDgg64MacYW8kG","messageID":"msg_e3368aa34001ZAxeUFDZu5KSUZ"}}
